      <h1>Kevin Heuzey</h1>
      <h2>Blockchain Infrastructure Architect & Tech Entrepreneur</h2>
    </div>

    <p>I am an Israeli tech entrepreneur, crypto infrastructure architect, and the founder of <a href="https://www.integrity.farm" target="_blank">Integrity.farm</a> — a blockchain protocol that redefines Bitcoin mining through on-chain emulation. By eliminating the need for physical hardware while leveraging real-time Bitcoin network data, Integrity.farm enables programmable, Bitcoin-backed incentives for Web3 platforms, gaming ecosystems, and decentralized economies.</p>

    <p>In 2015, I launched Ethereum Garden<sup>[1]</sup>, one of the earliest decentralized Ethereum mining networks in Eastern Europe. Built entirely from scratch in Odessa, Ukraine and fully bootstrapped, the project scaled rapidly to over 2,500 GPUs at a time when institutional capital had yet to enter the sector. In 2016, it was featured by Gazeta.ua<sup>[1]</sup> as the first industrial crypto-mining farm in Europe, launched before the global crypto boom. Later, in 2018, it was profiled by Telegraf<sup>[2]</sup> as “the boldest mining project in Eastern Europe.” The project was acquired by a Ukrainian family office in late 2017.</p>

    <p>In 2016, I was selected for the Israel Tech Challenge<sup>[3]</sup>, a government-backed program focused on AI, cybersecurity, and blockchain. Led by veterans of Israel’s elite intelligence unit Unit 8200<sup>[4]</sup>, the program deepened my technical foundations in decentralized systems and national-scale infrastructure protection.</p>

    <p>From 2017 onward, I collaborated with cybersecurity experts in Eastern Europe, notably Volodymyr Taratushka<sup>[5]</sup>, co-founder of Hacken and the HackIT conference. I served as an advisor during HackIT’s transformation into Hacken the global Web3 security firm, contributing to early ecosystem strategies and architectural decisions related to blockchain-integrated cybersecurity. In the same year, I served as a jury member at the HackIT Cup<sup>[6]</sup> — a high-profile bug bounty and CTF competition sponsored by Fenbushi Capital<sup>[7]</sup> and attended by global figures such as Vitalik Buterin.</p>

    <p>In 2018, my leadership on blockchain-powered security systems continued through HackIT, with events featuring Phil Zimmermann (inventor of PGP)<sup>[8]</sup> and Steve Wozniak (Apple co-founder). Hacken, which emerged from this ecosystem, has since become one of the world’s most respected Web3 security firms, auditing over 1,200 projects including Binance, VeChain, Avalanche, KuCoin, and The Sandbox.</p>

    <p>In December 2017, I spearheaded the development of a 2.5 MW Tier 4 Bitcoin mining data center on the Nokia Paris-Saclay campus<sup>[9]</sup> — the largest in Central Europe at the time. Accelerated by the Nokia Bell Labs Startup Program, the facility served as the foundation for the Blockchain Research Institute, which I co-founded and directed until its closure in 2024. The institute focused on industrial-scale mining, energy reuse, and the convergence of physical infrastructure and cryptographic trust.</p>

    <p>Integrity.farm is my current venture, using smart contracts, Chainlink oracles, to emulate real-time mining performance on-chain. It allows NFT collections, DAOs, and play-to-earn games to distribute wBTC-based incentives that track real Bitcoin mining economics without issuing inflationary tokens or operating physical machines. Each digital asset minted on the protocol is collateralized and generates programmable rewards based on actual network difficulty, block rewards, and hashrate creating an auditable, transparent, and decentralized incentive system.</p>

    <p>Today, I focus on designing verifiable, trustless financial infrastructure, bridging real-world energy systems with transparent, on-chain reward mechanisms. I also advise a European aerospace company on innovation at the intersection of autonomous systems, defense, and blockchain-based architectures.</p>

    <p>I write frequently about Web3 architecture, Bitcoin mining economics, zero-knowledge systems, and the evolution of blockchain from speculative hype toward applied, measurable utility — across both digital and industrial domains.</p>

